related_questions.question: What does it mean when people are vanilla?
related_questions.snippet: It is often used to describe someone who is perceived as plain, average, or unadventurous in their choices or activities. The term "vanilla" is commonly used metaphorically to imply a lack of distinctiveness or a preference for simplicity in various contexts, such as food, relationships, or personal style.
related_questions.title: Understanding the Meaning of Being 'Vanilla' in Different Contexts - TikTok

related_questions.question: What is the meaning of the word vanilla?
related_questions.snippet: Vanilla is the flavor for food — such as ice cream — that contains extract from the vanilla plant. This word also describes things that are boring or plain. If something is called vanilla — such as coffee or a milkshake — it's usually flavored with vanilla extract or the seeds from a vanilla pod.
related_questions.title: Vanilla - Definition, Meaning & Synonyms - Vocabulary.com

related_questions.question: What is vanilla extract made out of?
related_questions.snippet: Vanilla extract is made by soaking vanilla beans in a mixture of water and ethyl alcohol ( 1 ). The extract gets its signature vanilla flavor from a molecule called vanillin found in vanilla beans ( 1 , 2).

related_questions.snippet: Vanilla goes by similar names in different languages such as fan ni lan (Chinese), vanila (Hindi), vainilla (Spanish), vanille (French), fanilya (Arabic), vaniglia (Italian), and vanille (German).

buttons.subtitle: Where Does Vanilla Come From?
buttons.title: Where Does Vanilla Extract Come From? | Bon Appétit
buttons.snippet: To understand vanilla extract, you've got to know the basics about vanilla. First off, a vanilla bean is no bean—it's actually the fruit of orchids in the genus Vanilla. Those vanilla orchids only grow in a very small subsection of the world, with Madagascar producing a whopping 80%.

buttons.subtitle: Vanilla Sugar
buttons.title: Vanilla sugar - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: Vanilla sugar can be prepared by combining 400 g (2 cups) of white sugar with the scraped seeds of one vanilla bean. It can also be made by adding 1 to 2 whole vanilla beans to an airtight jar with 200 to 400 g (1 to 2 cups) of white sugar, and aging the mixture for two weeks; the sugar can be replaced as it is used.

buttons.subtitle: Vanilla Extract Substitute
buttons.title: A Baker's Guide to the (Many) Types of Vanilla - Real Simple
buttons.snippet: Beans, paste, extract—they all describe vanilla. As a general rule, if a recipe calls for vanilla beans, a teaspoon of either vanilla paste or vanilla extract can work as a great substitute. Alternately, you can use the seeds scraped from half a vanilla bean in place of a teaspoon of extract.
snippet_highlighted_words: a teaspoon of either vanilla paste or vanilla extract
